{"title":"Nonparametric Stochastic Contextual Bandits","domain":"RL","seeds":[{"problem":"Contextual bandits with unknown, highly non-linear reward functions per arm require algorithms that both identify the best arm across contexts and achieve low regret under mild assumptions.","method":"Estimate each arm’s mean reward with k-nearest-neighbor (k-NN) regression and act via a simple UCB policy (kNN-UCB) that selects the arm maximizing the k-NN estimate plus a confidence bonus scaling as n^{-1/(2+D)} up to logs. Using uniform sampling, the method achieves uniform over-context ε-optimal arm identification with sample complexity ~ ε^{-(2+D)}, matching nonparametric lower bounds up to logs. For online decision-making, it provides a high-probability (not just in expectation) sublinear regret bound of ~ T^{(1+D)/(2+D)} with a straightforward implementation (initial pulls per arm, per-arm k-NN estimators, and σ(n) bonuses)."},{"problem":"Nonparametric methods suffer from the curse of dimensionality when the ambient context dimension is high, even if data lie on a lower-dimensional structure.","method":"Assuming contexts lie on a d-dimensional smooth manifold embedded in R^D, leverage k-NN’s intrinsic-dimension adaptation to replace D by d in the uniform consistency rates. The same uniform sampling and kNN-UCB algorithms then attain ε-optimal identification with ~ ε^{-(2+d)} samples and high-probability regret ~ T^{(1+d)/(2+d)}, independent of the ambient dimension. This requires no preprocessing or manifold learning, relying solely on k-NN’s finite-sample guarantees under the manifold assumption."},{"problem":"A learned context-to-arm mapping does not reveal the topology of regions where each arm is optimal; practitioners may need the number and shapes of these regions.","method":"Construct a graph over sampled contexts where a chosen arm i is estimated to be top (via k-NN estimates), connecting points within a radius R, and return the graph’s connected components as the estimated regions. Under mild conditions (uniqueness of the top arm almost everywhere and component separations), this procedure consistently recovers both the correct number of components and their shapes in Hausdorff distance as samples grow, with R chosen below a separation-dependent threshold."}]}
